## 1. Overview

Selebox is a social platform with three first-class content types: **posts**, **videos**, and **books**. The website is a vanilla HTML/JS app. A separate mobile app (Appwrite-backed) shares some legacy content (videos + books) read-only on the web.

## 2. Stack

- **Database / Auth:** Supabase (Postgres + RLS + Realtime + Storage)
- **Video hosting / encoding:** Bunny.net Stream (separate "new" library for web, isolated from mobile's library)
- **Video playback:** HLS.js (inline in feed + dedicated player)
- **Rich text editor:** Quill 2.0 (CDN)
- **Edge Functions (Deno):** `bunny-upload`, `bunny-delete`, `bunny-webhook`
- **Mobile backend:** Appwrite (legacy; web reads books/videos collections via JS SDK, no writes)
- **Frontend:** Plain `index.html` + `app.js` (~10k lines) + `style.css`. No framework, no bundler. Admin panel is a separate `admin.html` + `admin.js` + `admin.css`.

## 3. Key Architectural Decisions

- **Postgres-first business logic.** Triggers + RPCs + RLS enforce rules. Edge Functions are reserved for things that must touch a 3rd-party API (Bunny). No app server.
- **Two Bunny libraries.** Web uploads go to a dedicated library via `BUNNY_*_NEW` env vars. The old (mobile) library is not touched by web Edge Functions ŌĆö `bunny-delete` actively refuses to operate on legacy library videos.
- **Lazy auth / claim-by-email.** Profiles can exist before `auth.users`. On first Supabase sign-in, `handle_new_user()` matches by email and adopts the legacy row. FKs use `on update cascade` so the swap is safe.
- **Polymorphic engagement.** `comments` works for posts and videos (mutually-exclusive `post_id` / `video_id`). `reactions` is polymorphic via `target_type` + `target_id`. `chapter_comments` is its own table (threaded).
- **Coalesced engagement notifications.** Likes/comments/reposts/book likes/chapter comments fan into one unread `notifications` row per `(recipient, type, target)` with an `actor_ids[]` array (capped at 20). Follower fan-out (new post / new book) stays uncoalesced because each event has a unique target.
- **Dual-source content.** Books and videos may originate from Supabase (web-native, full CRUD) or Appwrite (mobile, read-only). IDs are prefixed (`aw_`, `bk_`, `sb_`) to disambiguate at the boundary.
- **Reader anti-copy.** Chapter reader uses CSS `user-select: none` + right-click block + a deterministic watermark over content. Deterrent, not security.

